# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bobby-bragan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The **1940 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1940.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Cincinnati Reds and Detroit Tigers as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 37th World Series on October 2 and ended with Game 7 on October 8.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds defeated the Tigers, four games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1919.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1939 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The eighth All-Star Game was held on July 9 at Sportsman's Park in St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The 1940 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 16, featured all sixteen teams, the first since the 1936 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 29, which also saw all sixteen teams play, the first since the 1938 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time since 1934 that all sixteen teams played their first and last games on the same days.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 2 and October 8.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] 8 tie games (3 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 2 and ended on October 8 with the Cincinnati Reds defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1940 World Series in seven games.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] Over 82 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 49 games at Cleveland Stadium and 33 games at League Park.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] All Sunday home games took place at Cleveland Stadium.
[src:bobby-bragan/1940-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 6th of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The **1942 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1942.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 27, with the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 39th World Series on September 30 and ended with Game 5 on October 5.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] In the third iteration of this World Series matchup, the Cardinals defeated the Yankees, four games to one, capturing their fourth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1934.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1941 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The 10th All-Star Game was played on July 6 at the Polo Grounds in New York, New York, home of the New York Giants.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, the Brooklyn Dodgers had a record of 104–50, but finished two games behind the Cardinals; the Dodgers tied the 1909 Chicago Cubs, who had a record of 104–49, for the most wins in an MLB regular season without reaching the postseason.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics set a record for the fewest runs batted in during a season, with only 354.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns nearly moved to Los Angeles, California for the start of the 1942 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] During the 1941 Winter Meetings in Chicago, Illinois, a vote was scheduled for the morning of December 8, and was expected to be approved.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] However, due to the attack on Pearl Harbor by Japan the previous day (and subsequent entry of the United States into World War II), when it came time to vote, all teams (including the Browns) unanimously voted against the move.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The team would eventually leave for Baltimore, Maryland in 1954 where they remain today as the Baltimore Orioles, while Los Angeles would eventually get a major league team in 1958 when the Dodgers moved from Brooklyn, New York.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The 1942 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 16, featured all sixteen teams, the first since the 1940 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 27 and featured ten teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 30 and October 5.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] 9 tie games (2 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 30 and ended on October 5 with the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the New York Yankees in the 1942 World Series in five games.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Over 80 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 46 games at Cleveland Stadium and 34 games at League Park.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] All Thursday home games took place at League Park.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 8th of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] Following the reversion of the Boston Bees name to Boston Braves the previous season, National League Park's name was also reverted, to Braves Field.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds re-entered Willard Hershberger's No.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] 5 into circulation, only two years after his number was retired.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first number to be de-retired by any team in MLB.
[src:bobby-bragan/1942-major-league-baseball-season] His number would later be re-retired to honor Johnny Bench in 1984.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1943 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] This was the seventh season of the Negro American League.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] Birmingham and Chicago each won a half of the season, which therefore matched them up in a matchup to determine the champion for the NAL pennant to determine who would make the 1943 Negro World Series.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] Birmingham prevailed in five games to win their first ever pennant.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] This was the eleventh season of the second Negro National League.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] For the sixth time in seven seasons, the Homestead Grays won the pennant, this time under manager Candy Jim Taylor.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-in-baseball-p01] The Negro National League All Star team & Atlanta Black Crackers played against the two leagues.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The **1943 major league baseball season** began on April 20, 1943.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 40th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 5 on October 11.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] In the fourth iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Yankees defeated the Cardinals, four games to one, capturing their tenth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1941.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The 11th All-Star Game was held on July 13 at the Shibe Park in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, hosted by the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] This was also the first All-Star Game held at night.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] In order to conserve rail transport during World War II, the 1943 spring training sites was limited to an area east of the Mississippi River and north of the Ohio River.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] Spring training sites included the Chicago White Sox in French Lick, Indiana; the Washington Senators in College Park, Maryland; and the Yankees in Asbury Park, New Jersey.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The 1943 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 20 with a game between the Philadelphia Athletics and Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day took place on the following day, featuring four teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1941 that both leagues opened on different days.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 3, which saw all sixteen teams play, also the first time since 1941.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 11.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] 11 tie games (4 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 11 with the New York Yankees defeating the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals in the 1943 World Series in five games.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] Over 77 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 48 games at Cleveland Stadium and 29 games at League Park.
[src:bobby-bragan/1943-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 9th of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The **1944 major league baseball season** began on April 18, 1944.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 1, with the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Louis postseason, the postseason began with Game 1 of the 41st World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 6 on October 9.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals defeated the Browns, four games to two, capturing their fifth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1942.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1943 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The 12th All-Star Game was held on July 11 at the Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, home of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The season is notable for greatly relaxing restrictions on night games.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] This was Kenesaw Mountain Landis' last season of his 24-year tenure as commissioner, following his death in November.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] He would be succeeded by Happy Chandler.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Lewis of the *Pittsburgh Courier*, John H.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Sengstacke of *The Chicago Defender*, and Howard Murphy of the *Baltimore Afro-American,* to plead their case in favor of integration in baseball, marking the first time a black person had spoken directly with the leaders of Organized Baseball about this topic.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] However, it would not be until after Landis' death in November 1944 that baseball would begin to move towards breaking the color line.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The 1944 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 18, featuring fourteen teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 1, which saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend since the previous season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 9.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers defeating the Yankees and Giants, winning the game 5–1–0, respectively.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Including a $50 million donation from New York City, a total of $56 million (equivalent to $1.024 billion in 2025) was raised or the war effort.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] 11 tie games (3 in AL, 8 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 9 with the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns in the 1944 World Series in six games.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] Over 78 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 43 games at Cleveland Stadium and 35 games at League Park.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] All Saturday home games took place at League Park.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 10th of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:bobby-bragan/1944-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first number retired by the team.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The **1947 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1947.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 28, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 44th World Series on September 30 and ended with Game 7 on October 6.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup, the Yankees defeated the Dodgers, four games to three, capturing their 11th championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1943.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 14th All-Star Game was held on July 8 at Wrigley Field in Chicago, Illinois, home of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 1947 season is most notable as the year that the baseball color line broke, thanks to the Brooklyn Dodgers starting Jackie Robinson on Opening Day.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] On April 15, Opening Day for the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers, Jackie Robinson was in the Dodgers' lineup, playing first base against the Boston Braves at Ebbets Field.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] His appearance in a major league game broke the baseball color line, the practice of excluding players of black African descent.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Though he endured epithets and death threats, as well as a slow start, his skill would earn him the first ever Rookie of the Year award, named in Robinson's honor 40 years later.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Halfway through the season on July 5, the American League's Cleveland Indians debuted Larry Doby, becoming the first black player in the American League and breaking the AL color line.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Doby was a more low-key figure, suffered many of the same indignities that Robinson did, albeit with less press coverage.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Kansas City Monarchs star Willard Brown and teammate Hank Thompson briefly played for the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns, becoming the third and fourth Black players in either the NL or AL, and made the St.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns the first of either the NL or AL to field two Black players on one roster.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Brown was the first black player to hit a home run in the American League.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 1947 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 15, featuring all sixteen teams, continuing the trend from 1945.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 28, which also saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from the previous season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time since 1940 that all sixteen teams played their first and last games on the same days.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 30 and October 6.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] 11 tie games (7 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 30 and ended on October 6 with the New York Yankees defeating the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1947 World Series in seven games.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the Indians would typically play home games at League Park on weekdays and Cleveland Stadium on weekends.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play at Cleveland Stadium for a total of 60 seasons through 1993.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The **1947 World Series** matched the New York Yankees against the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Yankees won the Series in seven games for their 11th World Series championship in team history.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Yankees manager Bucky Harris won the Series for the first time since managing the Washington Senators to their only title in 1924, a gap of 23 years, the longest between World Series appearances in history.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In 1947, Jackie Robinson, a Brooklyn Dodger, desegregated major league baseball.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] For the first time in World Series history, a racially integrated team played.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] This was the first World Series televised.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] However, TV broadcasting was still in its infancy, and thus the series was only seen in four markets via coaxial inter-connected stations: New York City; Philadelphia; Schenectady/Albany, New York; Washington, D.C.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Outside of New York, coverage was pooled.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The stations in those markets affiliated with NBC televised games 1 and 5; the DuMont stations had games 2, 6, and 7, and those affiliated with CBS broadcast games 3 and 4.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] There was an announced crowd of 73,365 in Yankee Stadium for Game 1.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Brooklyn struck first in the first inning on Dixie Walker's RBI single off Spec Shea to score Pete Reiser from second base, but starter Ralph Branca was knocked out in a five-run fifth.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] A single, walk and hit-by-pitch loaded the bases before Johnny Lindell's two-run double put the Yankees up 2–1.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After a walk re-loaded the bases, another walk forced in a run, then after a groundout, Tommy Henrich's RBI single to left off Hank Behrman capped the inning's scoring.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Dodgers chipped away at the Yankees lead, getting a run in the sixth on Carl Furillo's RBI single off Joe Page and another in the seventh on Page's wild pitch with Pee Wee Reese at second, but Page held the Dodgers scoreless afterward as the Yankees took a 1–0 series lead.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Yankees struck first in Game 2 on Johnny Lindell's double-play ground ball after two leadoff singles in the first off Vic Lombardi, scoring Snuffy Stirnweiss, but the Dodgers tied the game in the third on Jackie Robinson's RBI single.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Yankees regained the lead in the bottom half of the inning on Lindell's RBI triple with a runner at third, but the Dodgers again tied the game in the fourth on Dixie Walker's home run.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the bottom half of the fourth, after a leadoff triple, Phil Rizzuto's RBI double put the Yankees back in front 3–2.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the next inning, Tommy Henrich's lead-off home run extended their lead to 4–2.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After a ground-rule double knocked Lombardi out of the game, George McQuinn's RBI single off Hal Gregg made it 5–2 Yankees.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Yankees added another run in the sixth on Lindell's sacrifice fly before breaking it open in the seventh.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After a leadoff single and wild pitch by Hank Behrman, Billy Johnson's RBI single made it 7–2 Yankees.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After a pop out and intentional walk, Reynolds's RBI single made it 8–2 Yankees.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Rex Barney relieved Behrman and allowed an RBI single to Snuffy Stirnweiss and threw a wild pitch that turned the Yanks' advantage to 10–2.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Dodgers scored one more run in the ninth on Spider Jorgensen's groundout off Allie Reynolds, who scattered nine hits in a complete-game win.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the second inning the Dodgers rang up six runs.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After a one-out walk, Bruce Edwards's double and Pee Wee Reese's single scored a run each.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] One out later, after a single and passed ball, Eddie Stanky's two-run double was the end for Yankee starter Bobo Newsom, but the runs kept coming with a Carl Furillo two-run double after a single off Vic Raschi.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The rest of the day, the Yankees pecked away.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Back-to-back RBI singles by Johnny Lindell and Joe DiMaggio off Joe Hatten made it 6–2 Dodgers in the third.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After the Dodgers scored a run in the bottom half of the third on Spider Jorgensen's RBI single after a hit-by-pitch and wild pitch by Karl Drews, Sherm Lollar hit an RBI double in the fourth after a walk and Snuffy Stirnweiss added an RBI single.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After two walks in the bottom half of the fourth off Spud Chandler, the Dodgers got those runs back on back-to-back RBI singles by Dixie Walker and Gene Hermanski, but Joe DiMaggio hit a two-run home run in the fifth after a walk.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Tommy Henrich's RBI double in the next inning and Yogi Berra's home run in the seventh off Ralph Branca made it 9–8 Dodgers.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Reliever Hugh Casey set down Billy Johnson, Phil Rizzuto and Berra in order in the ninth.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Yankees entered Game 4 aiming to take a three games to one lead in the best-of-seven series, and came one out away from doing this.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] They scored a run in the first on a bases-loaded walk off Harry Taylor and another in the fourth on Johnny Lindell's double after a leadoff triple off Hal Gregg.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Bill Bevens, the Yankee starter, pitched 8+2⁄3 innings without allowing a base hit, but allowed a run in the fifth on Pee Wee Reese's fielder's choice after two walks and a sacrifice bunt.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] No pitcher had ever thrown a no-hitter in a major league World Series game.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Going into the bottom of the ninth inning, Bevens and the Yankees led 2–1.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Bevens got Bruce Edwards to fly out, and then walked Carl Furillo.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Spider Jorgensen fouled out for the 2nd out.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Pete Reiser pinch-hit for pitcher Hugh Casey; during the at-bat, Gionfriddo stole second base.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Yankees then intentionally walked Reiser.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Eddie Miksis pinch-ran for Reiser, and the Dodgers sent Cookie Lavagetto to pinch-hit for Eddie Stanky.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Lavagetto lined a 1–0 fastball to right field; the ball ricocheted off the wall with a peculiar bounce and hit Yankee right fielder Tommy Henrich in the shoulder, as Gionfriddo and Miksis raced around to score.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The play ended the no-hitter and won the game for the Dodgers.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The hit was the last of Lavagetto's career.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Additionally, neither Lavagetto nor Bevens nor Gionfriddo would play in the majors again following this Series.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Dodgers, with this hit, avoided a three-games-to-one deficit, avoided becoming the victim of a no-hitter, and tied the Series at two games each.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The rapid and dramatic reversal of fortunes may have provided a momentum swing.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] As was the case in their only previous World Series encounter six years earlier, the Yankees and Dodgers again played a dramatic Game 4 which was decided on a lead change with two outs in the ninth inning.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In both instances the Yankees entered the game with a 2–1 series lead and Hugh Casey ended up being the pitcher of record for the Dodgers (losing in 1941, winning in 1947).
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Game 4 was the first of three times that the Dodgers won a World Series game after trailing through eight innings.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] This would also happen in 1988 during Game 1, and in 2025 during Game 7.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Nine walks in fewer than five innings proved the undoing of Rex Barney in this start for Brooklyn.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] A pair of walks and RBI single by opposing pitcher Spec Shea in the fourth put the Yankees up 1–0.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Joe DiMaggio homered to left in the fifth.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] That was all the runs the visiting Yanks would get at Ebbets Field, but this was all Shea needed.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] A hit by Jackie Robinson in the sixth scored Al Gionfriddo to pull the Dodgers within 2–1.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Then in the ninth, after a Bruce Edwards leadoff single and sacrifice bunt by Carl Furillo, the tying run died on base.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Shea got Spider Jorgensen on a fly to right, and with Brooklyn's fans on their feet, pinch-hitter Cookie Lavagetto struck out.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Dodgers won Game 6 to force a seventh and deciding game.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Three straight singles loaded the bases in the first with no outs, then Dixie Walker's double play and Allie Reynolds's passed ball scored a run each.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the third, three straight doubles by Pee Wee Reese, Jackie Robinson and Walker made it 4–0 Dodgers.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, after a double and wild pitch by Vic Lombardi, an error on Snuffy Stirnweiss's ground ball allowed a run to score.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After a single, Johnny Lindell's RBI single cut the Dodgers' lead to 4–2.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After another single knocked Lombardi out of the game, RBI singles by Billy Johnson and Bobby Brown off Ralph Branca tied the game.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Yogi Berra's RBI single next inning put the Yankees up 5–4.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the sixth, after a leadoff single and double off Joe Page, Cookie Lavagetto's sacrifice fly tied the game, then Bobby Bragan's RBI single put the Dodgers up 6–5.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] A single knocked Page out of the game, then Reese's two-run single off Bobo Newsom made it 8–5 Dodgers.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] A catch made by Al Gionfriddo, replayed countless times, may be the most remembered play of this game, and one of the most remembered plays of the Series.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the last of the sixth, the Dodgers sent Al Gionfriddo to left field as a defensive replacement for Eddie Miksis.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] With two on and two outs, Joe DiMaggio came to bat for the Yankees, representing the potential tying run.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] DiMaggio drove the ball deep, and Gionfriddo quickly pedalled back to snare it just in front of the bullpen-alley fence, near the 415-foot (126 m) marker posted to the center field side of the bullpen alley (the sign on the left field side of the alley was posted as 402).
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Many announcers since that time have used variations of the call, especially Chris Berman of ESPN.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] These announcers have tended to describe the *ball itself* as going "back-back-back".
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In Barber's call, it was the *outfielder* who was going "back-back-back".
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Films of the play showed DiMaggio, heading for second, kick the dirt in disgust after he realized Gionfriddo had caught the ball.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] This was a surprise to many who witnessed it, since DiMaggio was known to never show his emotions while playing.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Three of the 1947 Series' prominent figures, Gionfriddo, Lavagetto and Bevens, finished their playing careers in this Series.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Gionfriddo did not play in Game 7, and his catch of DiMaggio's drive was his only put-out in this game.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] So Gionfriddo's famous catch was his final put-out in his major league career.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The Yankees loaded the bases in the bottom of the ninth off Joe Hatten and Hugh Casey, but scored only once on a groundout.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The scoring began in the second inning, when the Dodgers strung together four consecutive hits: three off of Yankee starter Spec Shea, and a fourth off of reliever Bill Bevens, to put the Dodgers ahead, 2–0, in the top half of the inning.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Gene Hermanski tripled, Bruce Edwards drove Hermanski in with a single, and Carl Furillo followed with another single, prompting a pitching change.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Spider Jorgensen greeted reliever Bevens with a double, scoring Edwards for the second run.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the bottom half of the second inning, the Yankees cut the lead to 2–1.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After Dodger starter Hal Gregg issued two walks, Phil Rizzuto delivered an RBI single, scoring George McQuinn.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the bottom of the fourth, the Yankees took the lead with a two-out rally.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] With two runners on, Bobby Brown, pinch-hitting for Bevens, doubled off of Gregg, scoring Billy Johnson to tie the game.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] After a walk loaded the bases, Tommy Henrich stroked an RBI single, scoring Rizzuto and putting the Yankees up 3–2.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] With this lead, Yankee pitcher Joe Page entered the game to begin the top of the fifth inning, and would close the game out.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Over the next five innings, Page retired 13 consecutive Dodger batters.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] During this time, the Yankees added two runs.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Rizzuto lead off the bottom of the sixth with a bunt single, and stole second base; Allie Clark drove him home with a single off of Joe Hatten, making the score 4–2.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In the bottom of the seventh, Aaron Robinson hit a sacrifice fly off of Hugh Casey, to score Billy Johnson, who had just tripled.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] In all, Page pitched five innings of one-hit, shutout relief.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] With one out in the top of the ninth, he allowed his first and only baserunner of the outing, when Eddie Miksis singled.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Page quickly recovered, inducing Edwards to ground into a double play that ended the game.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] This was the most recent World Series to end on a double play until 2025, which also involved the Dodgers, but this time as the winners, and which was also decided in seven games.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] For the first time, a World Series produced total receipts over $2 million: Gate receipts were $1,781,348.92, radio rights $175,000.00 and television rights $65,000.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Yogi Berra pinch-hit for Sherm Lollar in the seventh inning of Game 3 and hit the first pinch-hit home run in World Series history.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] This was the first World Series to be televised, although the games were only seen in a small number of Eastern markets with stations connected via coaxial cable: New York City, New York; Philadelphia, Pennsylvania; Schenectady, New York; Washington, DC; and environs surrounding these cities.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The October 18, 1947 edition of *Billboard* reported that a total of over 3.9 million people viewed the seven games, primarily on TV sets located in bars (*Billboard* estimated 5,400 tavern TV sets in NYC alone, with 4,870 in use).
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] The October 13, 1947, edition of *Time* magazine reported that President Truman, who had just made the first Oval Office TV appearance on October 5, 1947, and received the first TV for the White House, watched parts of the Series but "skipped the last innings".
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] At the direction of Commissioner Happy Chandler, the Series, for the first time, used six umpires to make calls.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] Series from 1918 through 1946 used four umpires in the infield, with two alternates available if needed.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] However, no alternate had ever been needed, and Chandler believed that enlisting these umpires to make calls along the outfield lines would put these men and their skills to better use.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] However, it was not until 1964 that the additional two umpires rotated into the infield during the course of the Series.
[src:bobby-bragan/1947-world-series] This was the first, and to date only, World Series in which the Yankees won Game 7 in their home stadium.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan played eight seasons with the Philadelphia Phillies and Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1940s, before going on to manage the Pittsburgh Pirates, Cleveland Indians and Milwaukee/Atlanta Braves in the late 1950s and 1960s.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He also managed in the Cuban League, leading Almendares to two championships.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] However, Bragan was ejected in the third inning of his "comeback", thus also becoming the oldest person in any capacity to be ejected from a professional baseball game.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan died on January 21, 2010, of a heart attack at his home in Fort Worth.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] A right-handed batter listed as 5 feet 10 inches (1.78 m) tall and 175 pounds (79 kg), Bragan hit .240 in 597 games, with 456 hits and 15 career home runs.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan missed the 1945–46 seasons performing military service.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He was commissioned a lieutenant in the United States Army and was stationed at Camp Wheeler, Georgia.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] In his only World Series appearance, in 1947 against the New York Yankees, he appeared in Game 6 as a pinch hitter; batting for Ralph Branca in the sixth inning with the game tied at five all, he doubled off Yankee relief pitcher Joe Page to drive home Carl Furillo with the eventual winning run.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan's hit gave him a perfect 1.000 career batting average in World Series play.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] During his Major League managerial career, Bragan never skippered a game past his 49th birthday.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He managed the Pittsburgh Pirates (1956–57), Cleveland Indians (1958), and Milwaukee / Atlanta Braves (1963–66), each time getting fired in the mid-season of his final campaign.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] In Cleveland, he lasted a total of only 67 games of his maiden season before his dismissal—at the time of his firing, his was the shortest managerial stint in team history.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] His career big-league managerial won–lost record was below .500: 443–478 (.481).
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He was the Braves' pilot during the transitional period when they relocated from Milwaukee to Atlanta.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan also was a Major League coach for the Los Angeles Dodgers (1960) and Houston Colt .45s (1962).
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Despite his lack of success in the majors, Bragan was highly respected as a minor league manager, winning championships in 1948 and 1949 with Fort Worth of the Double-A Texas League during a successful 41⁄2-year run, and with the 1953 Hollywood Stars of the Open-Classification Pacific Coast League.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] A photograph of Bragan lying at the feet of an umpire who had ejected him, still arguing, was published in *Life* magazine at the time.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan was a protégé of Branch Rickey, the Hall of Fame front-office executive, who hired him as an unproven young manager at Fort Worth in 1948.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Then 30 years old, Bragan had started the 1948 season with the Dodgers but played sparingly, getting into only nine games (starting two) through June 27, and collecting only two hits in a dozen at-bats.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] When Rickey wanted to make room for Roy Campanella, who was starring in the minors, he offered Bragan the Fort Worth managerial job; he took over in July 1948, and remained with the Cats through 1952.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Then, in 1953, Rickey, by now heading the Pittsburgh front office, brought Bragan to Hollywood and the Pirates' organization.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan had clashed with Rickey in 1947 over the Dodgers' breaking of the baseball color line after the big-league debut of Jackie Robinson.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan—the Dodgers' second-string catcher at the time—was one of a group of white players, largely from the American South, who signed a petition against Robinson's presence.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] "After just one road trip, I saw the quality of Jackie the man and the player", Bragan told MLB.com in 2005.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] As a manager, Bragan earned a reputation for "color-blindedness." When he was the skipper of the Dodgers' Triple-A Spokane Indians PCL farm club in 1959, he played a pivotal role in helping Maury Wills, a speedy African-American shortstop, rise to Major League stardom.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Wills' baseball career had stalled in the Dodgers' farm system until he learned to switch hit under Bragan.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He would fashion a 14-year MLB career, play on three world champions, make seven NL All-Star teams, and in 1962 win the National League Most Valuable Player Award and set a new record for stolen bases in a season, with 104 thefts, breaking Ty Cobb's 47-year-old mark.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] In his 1976 memoir *The Lords of Baseball*, longtime Dodger executive Harold Parrott would claim that Bragan's hiring by the Braves in 1963 was orchestrated by Rickey to thwart a plan by Dodger owner Walter O'Malley to replace his manager, eventual Hall of Famer Walter Alston, with Leo Durocher.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] The owner chose Milwaukee, fading as contenders and with a managerial vacancy to fill, as Alston's ideal destination.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] According to Parrott's memoir, Rickey—then in semi-retirement but still O'Malley's bitter enemy—discovered the scheme and brokered the marriage between Bragan and the Braves' ownership before O'Malley's plan could materialize.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Alston kept his job in Los Angeles and led the 1963 Dodgers to the world championship for his third Series triumph; he would remain at the Dodger helm through 1976, win three additional pennants and, in 1965, his fourth and final world title.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan scouted for the newborn Montreal Expos expansion franchise in 1968, and that October he agreed to return to uniform as a coach on Gene Mauch's staff for the team's maiden National League season in 1969.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] But before spring training could begin, in February 1969, Bragan stepped down to become president of the Double-A Texas League.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He was one of four color commentators used by the Expos during the 1972 season.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] A Fort Worth resident since 1948, Bragan spent seven seasons as president of the Texas League.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] His appointment came during a period of contraction and low attendance for minor league baseball; in 1971, the Texas circuit—down to only seven members when the El Paso franchise withdrew—temporarily merged with the Southern League to form the 14-club Dixie Association.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] With eight member clubs each, the Texas and Southern leagues resumed their former identities and were poised to capitalize on the attendance boom in the minor leagues that would follow during the 1980s.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bragan's achievements were recognized during the 1975–76 offseason when he was elected president of the minor leagues' governing body, the National Association of Professional Baseball Leagues, headquartered in Saint Petersburg, Florida.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He spent three full years as president of the minor leagues before he and his wife Gwenn returned to Fort Worth, where he joined the Texas Rangers' front office in 1979.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] He continued to make appearances and speaking engagements on behalf of the ballclub well into his eighties.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] After Gwenn Bragan's death in 1983, Bobby married Roberta Beckman.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] It was Roberta who suggested to Bobby that he establish a scholarship foundation to encourage youth to do well in school and go on to college.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] With the financial seed money provided by Roberta, the Bobby Bragan Youth Foundation (BBYF) was established in 1991.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Bobby married Betty Bloxam in 1995 and the two stayed together until his death.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Each year, the Bobby Bragan Youth Foundation honors outstanding athletes and executives for the achievements on and off of the playing field at the annual Bobby Bragan Gala to raise funds for the scholarships.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Honorees have included Joe DiMaggio, Hank Aaron, Larry King, Tommy Lasorda, Bobby Valentine, Bud Selig, Willie Mays, Lou Brock and Brooks Robinson.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] Five of the six Bragan boys played baseball professionally.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] His brother Jimmy was a minor league player and longtime coach and scout in Major League Baseball who himself was president of the Double-A Southern League during the 1980s.
[src:bobby-bragan/bobby-bragan] His brother Peter owned and operated the Jacksonville Suns of the Southern League for more than 25 years, and his son, Bobby Bragan Jr., operated the Elmira ball club in the New York–Penn League.
